The R Project for Statistical Computing

R is free software (under GNU GENERAL PUBLIC LICENSE).

It is available at http://www.r-project.org.

R was developed by Robert Gentleman and Ross Ihaka for teaching purposes, because of the high fees for SPLUS.

Today, the R Development Core Team consists of 20 people (among them S inventor John Chambers).

The most recent version is R-3.1.0.

The R Project for Statistical Computing

R is called R, because…

  • R is close to S,
  • Ross and Robert both start with an R,
  • They aimed at a “reduced version of S”.

To date there are 5447 packages available at CRAN (The Comprehensive R Archive Network), only counting packages available for all operating systems.

http://cran.r-project.org.

Useful commands: c() and length()

#Combine values into a vector or list
x <- c(7, 3, 4, 4, 3, 2)

#Length of a vector or list
length(x)

[1] 6

Useful commands: sort() and order()

x <- c(7, 3, 4, 9, 2)
y <- c(9, 2, 5, 1, 5)

sort(x)

[1] 2 3 4 7 9

order.x <- order(x)
y[order.x]

[1] 5 2 5 9 1

Useful commands: unique() and duplicated()

x <- c(7, 3, 4, 4, 3, 2)

unique(x)

[1] 7 3 4 2

duplicated(x)

[1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE

Useful commands: ls() and rm()

#List objects
ls()

[1] "order.x" "x"       "y"      

#Remove objects from the working environment
rm(order.x); ls()

[1] "x" "y"

rm(list=ls()); ls()

character(0)

Further useful functions and commands

Getting help

Once R is installed, there is a comprehensive built-in help system. At the program's command prompt you can use any of the following:

help.start()   # general help
help(foo)      # help about function foo
?foo           # same thing 

apropos("foo") # list all functions containing string foo
example(foo)   # show an example of function foo

# Search for foo in help manuals and archived mailing lists
RSiteSearch("foo")

# Get vignettes on using installed packages
vignette()      # show available vignettes
vignette("foo") # show specific vignette

Getting help

Examples:

help('sort')
help.search('unique')

Setup of help page:

  • Description
  • Usage
  • Arguments
  • Details

Basic descriptive statistics (more later)

One method for summary statistics is to use sapply():

# get means for variables in data frame mydata
# excluding missing values 
sapply(iris[,1:3], mean, na.rm=TRUE)

Sepal.Length  Sepal.Width Petal.Length 
       5.843        3.057        3.758 

sapply(iris[,1:3], var, na.rm=TRUE)

Sepal.Length  Sepal.Width Petal.Length 
      0.6857       0.1900       3.1163

More options: sd, min, max, median, range, quantile…

Basic descriptive statistics (more later)

There are numerous R functions that provide a range of descriptive statistics at once. For example:

# mean,median,25th and 75th quartiles,min,max
summary(iris[,1:3])

  Sepal.Length   Sepal.Width    Petal.Length 
 Min.   :4.30   Min.   :2.00   Min.   :1.00  
 1st Qu.:5.10   1st Qu.:2.80   1st Qu.:1.60  
 Median :5.80   Median :3.00   Median :4.35  
 Mean   :5.84   Mean   :3.06   Mean   :3.76  
 3rd Qu.:6.40   3rd Qu.:3.30   3rd Qu.:5.10  
 Max.   :7.90   Max.   :4.40   Max.   :6.90

Basic graphics

#Generic function for plotting of R objects
plot(x, y, ...)

#The generic function hist computes a histogram of the given data values.
hist(x, data, ...)

#Produce box-and-whisker plot(s) of the given (grouped) values.
boxplot(x, ...)

#Creates a bar plot with vertical or horizontal bars.
barplot(height, ...)

Additional options for plot():

lines(x, y, ...)
points(x, y, ...)
abline(...)

Basic graphics: plot()

par(mfrow=c(1,2), mar=c(4,4,1,1))
plot(iris[,3:4])
plot(iris[,3:4], pch=17, col="blue", cex=2)

Basic graphics: plot()

plot(iris[,3:4])
points(iris[1:50,3:4], pch=8, cex=2, col="green")

abline(h=0.75, col="blue")
abline(v=2.5, lty=2, lwd=2)

Basic graphics: plotting options

?points


?par

Several parameters can only be set by a call to par(), e.g.

  • “ask”,
  • “mai”, “mar”, “mex”, “mfcol”, “mfrow”, “mfg”,…
  • “new”,
  • “xlog”, “ylog”

Basic graphics: hist() and plot(density())

par(mfrow=c(1,2), mar=c(4,4,1,1))
hist(iris[,2])
plot(density(iris[,2]))

Basic graphics: boxplot() and stripchart()

par(mfrow=c(1,2), mar=c(4,4,1,1))
boxplot(Petal.Length ~ Species, data=iris)
stripchart(Petal.Length ~ Species, data=iris, pch=1, method="jitter", vertical=TRUE)

Basic graphics: barplot()

tab <- table(iris$Species)

as.data.frame(tab)

        Var1 Freq

3  virginica   50

barplot(tab)

Basic graphics: image() and contour()

image(volcano)


contour(volcano)

Statistical distributions: d/p/q/r functions

  • d<...>: Density
  • p<...>: Distribution function
  • q<...>: Quantile function
  • r<...>: Random number generation

Examples for distributions:

?Distributions

Statistical distributions: Normal dist.

dnorm(x, mean = 0, sd = 1, log = FALSE)

pnorm(q, mean = 0, sd = 1, lower.tail = TRUE, log.p = FALSE)

qnorm(p, mean = 0, sd = 1, lower.tail = TRUE, log.p = FALSE)

rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = 1)

Statistical distributions: Normal dist.

x <- seq(-3,3, by=0.01)
y <- dnorm(x=x)

plot(x=x, y=y, type="l")
